<p>It’s not quite right to say that for the first five years of its life, the iPad was an iPhone with a really big screen meant to be a lean-back consumption device. After all, the very first iPad shipped with a productivity accessory in the form of the <a href="https://apple.fandom.com/wiki/IPad_Keyboard_Dock">Keyboard Dock</a>.</p>
<p>But ten years ago, Apple got serious. It shipped the <a href="https://sixcolors.com/post/2015/11/ipadpro/">very first iPad Pro</a>, and began a decade-long conversation about whether the iPad could be used for work and even whether or not it was a computer.</p>
<p>Today, the M5 iPad Pro and iPadOS 26 have settled a lot of old scores. But it’s been a long, strange journey from <a href="https://sixcolors.com/post/2015/09/notebook-apples-newest-product-announcements/">“Hey Siri” day in San Francisco</a> to now.</p>
